segments.text: This is an interview with George Allen Bikima by Stephanie Lawson on Saturday, April 28, 1991 at a friend's home concerning the counterculture of the 1960s.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I am asking you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that alright with you?
Yes.
Okay, what is the date and place of your birth?
Dublin, Texas, 1950, October 1st.
Okay.
Where did you receive your high school education and your college education?
High school education was Waltrip High School in Houston and Stephen F. Austin in Nacogdoches.
Okay.
Where are you currently living and what is your current occupation?
I'm living in Houston and my current occupation is sales.
Okay.
When and where did you get involved in the hippie movement?
Probably my senior year in high school, 69.
Okay, and that was in Houston?
That was in Houston.
Okay.
Why did you join the counterculture?
Well, like everything else now, you had to join or be left out.
You know, peer pressure, you know.
Okay.
Well, how did your lifestyle change as you became a hippie?
Like, in your dress, in your music, hairstyles, food?
Well, everybody grew long hair.
Everybody changed their way of dress.
The attitude was do your own thing in your own time, in your own space, in your own way.
Did you dress any certain way?
I just tried to be, I guess, look rebellious, you know, like before
generation.
You remember that?
We've studied that.
Did music have a big effect on you?
Oh yeah.
Jimi Hendrix, The Stones, Janis Joplin.
A lot of those people are not with us today because of, I guess, drugs and all that.
Is that what you listen to?
Oh yeah.
What was your overall attitude during this time?
Did you have any slogans or sayings that were your trademark?
I didn't have any slogans.
Freedom and peace was just the cry of the youth movement at that time.
Okay.
Did you ever protest or march against the Vietnam War or anything else?
Yeah, we did that in our first semester at Stephen F. Austin in Nacogdoches.
We had a walkout planned and all the students on a certain day walked out of class and didn't return back to class for the full day.
That blew them away.
Why did you do this?
Well, we felt that at that time

Everything was so conservative and then all of a sudden our government as a whole went into a war that really wasn't ever declared a war and was killing people in our age group and it was just an overall bad move that the kids of our time just could not understand.
How do you think that living in the South, does it be different from living in other places like California or up north or something like that?
Living in the South, how is it different for you than you think like living in California, going to Berkeley, something like that?
I think it was different in the South because I think things started
eastward, and then all the affluent people up in the north, they got more newsprint than the people in the south.
Did you ever join a commune or experience any type of communal living?
Yes, I did.
I rebelled against my parents and left and lived in Mexico for three to four months.
and came back and then moved to New Orleans and stayed there for about three months and lived with several groups of people in the same dwelling.
Okay.
Why did you do this?
Just being rebellious, trying to let the establishment
Everybody else, school, government, we were going to do our own thing in our own time.
To be a hippie, did you have to do drugs?
And if you did or didn't, why?
Well, I don't think you had to do drugs.
I think it was pretty widespread back then.
The most common drug back then was just marijuana.
And, you know, just everybody did it.
Did drugs have any particular impact on you?
No, not really, because it was just recreational.
It wasn't anything that the people I ran around with
The group that I ran around with did not get into that, but we knew a lot of people that did and really got messed up, really went to the extreme.
Did any of your friends ever overdose or anything like that that would really impact you?
Yeah, I lost my best friend.
He overdosed.
He went out with a different crowd than what we ran around with and shot some heroin that we found out later, his parents found out later, that was almost pure.
And it just killed him.
Did you ever read or know of any underground newspapers and which ones were they?
I can't remember the name of it, but there was always a paper circulating telling about the movement of the youth back in that time.
What organizations or sit-outs or gatherings or things that were going on that people needed to attend.
You know, they were trying to get everybody in numbers to really show the establishment back then that there was really something going on.
What was the impact of women's liberation on you?
Did you feel that at all?
I never did really feel that.
I guess it was, you know, we could see it coming.
You know, more women were getting involved in the protests, especially on campus.

They were making just as much noise as the males of that time and it was just at that particular time it wasn't something that was really noticed because everybody was trying to group together, everybody was trying to unite and it was just thought of as pulling together as one.
Did you know any women that after the movement got started tried to go off on their own and have a women's movement type thing?
Not really.
I was never, you know, knew anybody like that.
I'm sure that happened.
You know, examples like Patty Hearst and that situation.
You know, that's all I can really think of at this time.
Okay and what impacted like sexual liberation or the sexual freedom that was going on have on you or did you see any of that?

Oh yeah that you know that went on it was you know when I went to high school it was completely different than after my first year of college when when all this was taking place it was you know there's a lot of communal living back then and you know you just
You know, you had sex and relationships with several different women, but that just didn't happen back in your high school days.
Okay.
What did you think about Charles Manson?
Did that affect you in any way?
Well, you know, everybody heard about it.
It just seemed like one of those things that happened in California where somebody went to the extreme, took a situation to the extreme.
And just, you know, it hurt.

I think on the overall, it hurt the movement because this guy had taken, you know, and his group had taken something that we thought had some substance to it and then just wiped the newspapers with blood with it.
So he did more harm for it than anything?
Yeah, I think so.
I don't think anybody condoned what happened, you know, with that situation.
I don't think anybody approved of it.
It was something that just happened and, you know, the hippie movement or the freedom
movement got blamed for it, and I don't think that was really the case.
I think something like that could happen today easily, which it probably does.
It just wasn't blown out of proportion like it was then.
I mean, not that it was any slight thing, but... Well, what is the craziest or most rebellious thing that you ever did that you can tell me?
It was like, tell about your hippie days.
We got into a, we blew up a telephone booth.
That was pretty rebellious.

For some reason we thought that was making an impact in our particular area for, you know, just one night we decided, well, we need to do something to let everybody know that there's something going on.
And so that's what we did.
Okay, what did your family think about this?
It stood them on their heads.
They couldn't figure it out because my sister was two years older than myself and they never experienced any of that with her.
And my brother was several years younger, well five years younger than myself and they didn't experience anything like that with him.
It was just that late 60s movement there that got caught up and
the late 60s and early 70s with the war and all that and that's what happened.
Well do you think that your rebellion was more toward the establishment or was it toward your parents or was it just a mixture of all authority?
Well it was the establishment
was everything involved.
Your parents, your professors at school, anybody that tried to tell you what to do, how to do it, when to do it, they were the establishment.
You were trying to prove your case to them that you weren't going to do what was expected of you at that particular time like everybody else before you.
That times were changing.
start rebelling.
Okay, is there any particular reason that you got out of the counterculture or why it ended?
Well, it just lost momentum and then you started figuring out that you had to do something with your life.
You couldn't continue doing what you were doing and you had to make something out of your life.
You couldn't make a lifelong
career out of, you know, a mood at that time.

And you just, everybody just went their separate ways and settled back down and finished school and got into different professions and started getting married and having families and, you know, it just slowed his pace.
Okay.
How did being a hippie in the 60s influence the rest of your life?
What do you think
left the biggest mark on you?
I think the biggest mark it left on me was to be more open-minded towards people's opinions or feelings or expectations and don't have such a closed-door attitude.
be open-minded, keep your opinions to yourself, let everybody else express their opinions, and try to reach a happy medium between the parties.
See, back then it was, nobody wanted to listen to the movement back then.
They just thought, you know, it was just something that was going to pass in a short period of time, which it didn't.
So that's what happened, you know, with the Woodstock deal and
I think that was August 1969 that happened, and the free love and the peace, and Richie Havens getting on stage, opening up with Freedom.
Did you go?
No, I wish I'd have gone.
I had an opportunity to go, and we decided it would be too much of a hassle to get up there, because back then, it's not like today.
We didn't have our own cars, and the people that had their own cars, we just couldn't swing it.
But I'd love to have gone.
All the big people back then, Janis Joplin, Jimi Hendrix, Richie Havens, all the big movement people and entertainers were there.
Do you regret being a part of the hippie movement?
No, not at all.
I think it's made the people that made it through a lot stronger.
It's hard to explain.
It's something that I'm glad that I made it through and didn't go to the extreme overdose on drugs or do crazy things, blow myself up or any of that stuff.
I think it's just the people that are running this country right now probably went through the same movement.
probably opened up their minds and hearts a little bit for other people's feelings.
What impact do you think the 60s made on America today?
I think the impact that the 60s made, this happened for today, is I think back then we were trying to reach a happy medium.
And it never did take place.
And now I think it's overcorrected itself.
The kids today have more freedom, more things to do, more money, more time to do it.
Parents seem not to be so strict on their kids.
They have more opportunities to do things.
And I think that's what the 60s did for the kids of today.
They have a better opportunity, a better chance.
They live better.
They have more money.
They have more time to do it.
I hope that's not off base when somebody hears this.
No, that's good.
Is there anything that you would like to add to this that would enrich other people about the 60s that would maybe help them understand it better?
I think the bottom line of the 60s was...

after all these years after World War II and Korea and all and it was very conservative type atmosphere and then it came to just a boiling point that things had to change and what happened in the 60s late 60s early 70s it went to the through the it just went 180 to the other extreme
And now today I think it's somewhere in between.
I'm not sure we're right where we need to be, but it's better.
Do you think Vietnam played a big impact on the movement to get it going that fast?

Oh sure, because all the people that I knew at that time and all the movements that I attended and all that, we just couldn't understand why a conservative type atmosphere with all the establishment and the government
All of a sudden, they made decisions to put people in our age group on a front line in a war that they didn't really want to win.
You know, it was costing our generation lives, not their generation.
They were making the decisions, and it was just not a conservative type attitude by the government to go into that war.
And I think that's why we really started rebelling.
Thank you very much.
Oh, you're welcome.
